\viewkind4\uc1\pard\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx204\lang1033\b\f0\fs20 GEORGE \b0\fs18 PLATEN \f1\fs22 could not conceal the longing in his voice. It was too much to suppress. He said, \ldblquote Tomorrow\rquote s the first of May. Olympics!\rdblquote\f0\par
\pard\fi249\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx249\f1 He rolled over on his stomach and peered over the foot of his bed at his roommate. Didn\rquote t \i\f0 he \i0\f1 feel it, too? Didn\rquote t \i\f0 this \i0 make some impression on him?\par
\f1 George\rquote s face was thin and had grown a trifle thinner in the nearly year and a half that he had been at the House. His figure was slight but the look in his blue eyes was as intense as it had ever been, and right now there was a trapped look in the way his fingers curled against the bedspread.\f0\par
\f1 George\rquote s roommate looked up briefly from his book and took the op\f0\-poffimity to adjust the light-level of the stretch of wall near his chair. His name was Hali Omani and he was a Nigerian by birth. His dark brown skin and massive features seemed made for calmness, and mention of the Olympics did not move him.\par
\f1 He said, \ldblquote I know, George.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 George owed much to Hall\rquote s patience and kindness when it was needed, but even patience and kindness could be overdone. Was this a time to sit there like a statue built of some dark, warm wood?\f0\par
George wondered if he himself would grow like that after ten years here and rejected the thought violently. No!\par
\f1 He said defiantly, \ldblquote I think you\rquote ve forgotten what May means.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 The other said, \ldblquote I remember very well what it means. It means nothing! You\rquote re the one who\rquote s forgotten that. May means nothing to you, George Platen, and,\rdblquote  he added softly, \ldblquote it means nothing to me, Hali Omani.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 George said, \ldblquote The ships are coming in for recruits. By June, thousands and thousands will leave with millions of men and women heading for any world you can name, and all that means nothing?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Less than nothing. What do you want me to do about it, anyway?\rdblquote  Omani ran his finger along a difficult passage in the book he was reading and his lips moved soundlessly.\f0\par
\fs20\page\pard\fi249\sl-238\slmult0\tx249\fs22 George watched him. Damn it, he thought, yell, scream; you can do that much. Kick at me, do anything.\par
It was only that he wanted not to beso alone in his anger. He wanted not to be the only one so filled with resentment, not to be the only one dying a slow death.\par
\f1 It was better those first weeks when the Universe was a small shell of vague light and sound pressing down upon him. It was better before Omarn had wavered into view and dragged him back to a life that wasn\rquote t worth living.\f0\par
Omani! He was old! He was at least thirty. George thought: Will I be like that at thirty? Will I be like that in twelve years?\par
